<section xml:id="lesson5_5" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Revisiting Gate Understanding</title>

<p>Learning how to perform the mathematics behind quantum state and operations unlocks 
two important quantum computing-related skills:</p>
<ul>
      <li>Better understanding how operations work when inputs are in superposition</li>
      <li>Learning the counter-intuitive properties of phase that are key to 
      critical quantum algorithms</li>
    </ul>

<p> We will revisit quantum gates now, and we will delve deeper into phase in the next chapter.</p>

<p>
We first introduced the truth tables for gates in a way analogous to digital computing. 
We will revisit those same gates now with our eye towards superposition.
</p><p>
Instead of using specific inputs, we will generalize to variable inputs. 
</p><p>
For a single qubit operation, our starting state will be:
